    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="preparation">re: Consensus Conferences, ex: Hakken</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="11" relname="span">

They seem, indeed, to be a good idea and to give all sides of a
technological issue a chance to argue and respond.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="9" relname="span">  NOH has been
running these for a long time now. </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="3" relname="elaboration"> Among those with which I have
had something to do, and from which I learned a great deal (not
all of it, by any means, encouraging) about the outsiders&apos;
(non-science) view of things----sorry, that&apos;s NIH, above, not
NOH----concerns and wishes, were those on diagnostic ultrasound
in pregnancy, animal experimentation and its alternatives,
cardiovascular medicine, diabetes, and so on.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="6" relname="concession">  The NIH method is
not quite the Danish one (as Hakken describes it),</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="10" relname="span"> but it has a
similar purpose and effect. </segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="12" relname="span"> The trouble is, decent and socially
conscious activities of this kind never get coverage in the media
or by academic commentators on science and technology.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="7" relname="nonvolitional-cause">  They have
little or no interpretable aspects of Privilege or Hegemony.</segment>
